<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-320-780  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 320 780.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 9 1990 v24 n15 p107(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bid protests no big deal for feds. (federal agencies not floodedwith protests over computing contract bids)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Protests over federal contract awards for computer equipment areless common than the public believes.andP;  The federal governmentawarded 2,475 contracts for computer goods and services in thesecond half of FY 1988, and a General Accounting Office reportindicates that only 123 of these were protested by disgruntledvendors.andP;  The majority of the protests were settled by the partiesthemselves; 15 were decided for protesters and 22 for thegovernment.andP;  Instances in which an agency pays off a protester arealso relatively rare.andP;  Most of the $1.5 million in payoffs in FY1985 can be traced to a single case in which the US Bureau of theCensus paid $1.1 million to three protesting vendors.andP;  Consultantswarn that excessive agency concerns about protests are a sign ofineptitude.andP;  Protests have become more visible today because moreof them go to the General Services Administration appeals board.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government ContractsCompetitive BiddingGovernment AgencyComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>